Note
In FY 2027, Program Element (PE) 0605057F, Next Generation Air-refueling System, Project 640010, NGAS efforts were transferred to PE 0604343F, Advanced Tanker
Systems (ATS), Project 640013, Advanced Tanker Systems, in order to continue developing and integrating platform-agnostic systems that comply with military open-
source architecture standards to ensure rapid adaptability and interoperability across platforms.

A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
Developing future tanker capability and recapitalizing the Air Force's aging tanker fleet is a top priority for the Department of the Air Force. In FY 2024, the Department
of the Air Force amended its previous Tanker recapitalization approaches (KC-X, KC-Y, KC-Z) in favor of more agile methods, prioritizing and accelerating the right
capabilities to deliver fuel to the fight. The FY 2024 Analysis of Alternatives (AoA) provided conclusions that tankers will need to be more survivable to operate in a
contested environment to include but not limited to examining the effectiveness and affordability of more resilient, connected, and survivable tanker systems.

 The Next Generation Air-refueling System (NGAS) program will develop more advanced capabilities to allow tankers to operate in a more contested environment. Future
 tanker fleet survivability capabilities are a top priority for the Department of the Air Force to counter pacing threats and enable B-21, CCAs, F-47, survivable tankers, and
 Space assets in contested environments.

 In FY 2027, NGAS will continue modeling and simulation support, planning for transition of new technologies for resilient connectivity and survivability (mission systems),
 and further market research. The Future Tankers System Program Office (SPO) will evaluate, research and pursue cost versus capability analysis, updated tanker
 models and high-fidelity modeling and simulation to further exercise joint warfighting concepts and plans. NGAS program Research, Development and Test (RDT&E)
 funding will allow for continued concept refinement and early risk reduction efforts to support continued requirements development and identify refined system attributes.

 This requirement supports performance of a full financial audit as required by title 10 U.S.C Chapter 9A, Sec 240-D.

 This program element included all necessary expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver weapon system capability. The use of such program funds would be in
 addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program elements 0605829F, 0605831F, 0605833F, and 0605898F.

 This effort is in Budget Activity 4, Advanced Component Development and Prototypes (ACD&P), because efforts are necessary to evaluate integrated technologies,
 representative modes or prototype systems in a high fidelity and realistic operating environment.


