INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0605502S$$, 2027, $$Defense Logistics Agency’s (DLA's) ability to deliver Americans the right logistics solution in every transaction requires more than successful management of the
Agency's wholesale supplies and suppliers. It requires supply chain excellence. Our military's ability to generate and sustain combat readiness indefinitely, anywhere
on the globe requires that DLA-managed materiel flow seamlessly and as needed from the nation's industrial base to where it is ultimately used.

 DLA's Small Business Innovative Research (SBIR) program seeks to solicit innovative research and development proposals from the small business community to
 address DLA’s strategic and operational requirements. All selections shall demonstrate and involve some technical risk with yet to be determined technical feasibility.
 Phase I proposals should demonstrate the feasibility of the proposed technology and provide a strong business case for Phase II investment for a prototype or at least a
 proof-of-concept demonstration. A favorable return on investment and commercialization potential have a strong influence on Phase II selections.$$, $$The Small Business Innovation Program (SBIP) explores innovative concepts pursuant to Public Law 106-554 (Small Business Reauthorization Act of 2000) and Public
Law 107-50 (Small Business Technology Transfer Program Reauthorization Act of 2001), which mandates a two-phase competition for small businesses with innovative
technologies with a defense application as well as a commercial value. The Small Business Innovation Research (SBIR) and Small Business Technology Transfer
(STTR) programs will develop new dual-use technologies for possible future DLA operational and sustainment requirements. DLA strives to make it fast and easy for
customers to work with our Agency by quickly understanding current requirements and anticipating their future needs. In support of the major subordinate commands
and military Services, Small Business Innovation Research (SBIR) helps to ensure readiness and lethality across the end-to-end supply chain by optimizing retail and
industrial support, which ultimately reduces risk and increases efficiency, and positions solutions for Warfighter requirements.

 Dual-use means the technologies will be judged on their potential for future private sector investment both as a vehicle for reducing development time and cost, unit
 costs of new DLA technologies, and as a route to national economic growth through new commercial products. DLA will conduct the competition as well as award and
 manage the contracts.

 The DLA's SBIR/STTR investments are divided into multiple Research Areas that are aligned with the National Defense Strategy and the DLA Strategic Plan.

 DLA R&D SBIP Strategic Focus Areas
 Hypersonic Vehicles: To meet increasing demand for hypersonic vehicle production, SBIP addresses the key bottleneck in the supply chain by producing innovations in
 thermal protection systems (TPS). Driving down lead times and production costs are critical to meeting hypersonic vehicle production capacity requirements in the near
 future.
 -Domestic Critical Mineral Production: To buffer US supply chains from disruption due to raw material availability, SBIP fosters innovation in domestic separation and
 refining capabilities to produce rare earth and other critical minerals at costs that are competitive in global markets.
 -Reshoring Defense Critical Materials: To reestablish domestic expertise and production facilities for defense critical materials such as permanent magnets and Li-Ion
 batteries, SBIP develops next generation technologies and circular economies to ensure the DoD is insulated from export restrictions placed on key components used in
 a range of platforms.
 - Supply Chain Innovation: To maintain a secure and resilient supply chain, SBIP provides opportunities for our small business industrial base to engage in
 technological innovations that enhance supply chain operations, improve procurement lead times, and reduce life cycle costs.

 DMEA
 - Advanced microelectronics concepts, technologies, and applications

 - Continue to seek innovative technical solutions to DOD microelectronics research and development needs and increase private sector commercialization of these
 innovations.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                    FY 2025     FY 2026      FY 2027
Title: SBIR Accomplishments/Plans                                                                                                          9.711       0.000        0.000
Description: DLA FY 2025 SBIR/STTR Accomplishments ($5.568M):
-Established and developed domestic suppliers for critical and strategic materials. Successfully developed 5 SBIR Phase I
recycling/recovery technologies for Gallium (Ga) from large domestic waste streams. Gallium is a key element in many defense
systems, including advanced radar.
-Continued bolstering the Thermal Protection System (TPS) supply network for hypersonic weapons through technological
innovations and elimination of single point failures. Reduction of TPS production time and cost is critical to meeting expanding
military offensive and homeland defense requirements.
-Initiated multiple projects to develop domestic and friendly supply networks of Scandium (Sc is a rare earth element) and
Scandium Oxide to form Aluminum-Scandium (Al-Sc) alloys with superior strength-to-weight and weldability properties for Additive
Manufacturing of advanced components for defense aerospace and marine applications.
-Sponsored a highly successful effort to recover boron carbide (B4C) from end-of-life Enhanced Small Arms Protective Inserts
(ESAPI - hard ceramic body armor for the Warfighter). Recovered B4C is crushed into a MIL SPEC powder will supply ESAPI
manufacturers and the National Defense Stockpile (NDS).
-Transitioned a Potassium Nitrate (KNO3) production effort to Phase III to complete the only domestic KNO3 pilot line. KNO3 is
the primary ingredient (oxidizer) in black powder, widely used for weapon systems.
-Continued developing multiple domestic production lines of high purity graphite for battery and solid rocket motor applications.
Matured transition opportunities to provide these materials to DoD prime contractors for use in a range of platforms.
-Grew Small Business capability to combat repair part sourcing challenges associated with weapon system aging, obsolescence,
and DMSMS through innovation, reverse engineering, and advanced manufacturing techniques.
-Developed networks of supply for various weapon systems impacted by obsolescence including the B-1, B-2, and B-52 bombers,
Intercontinental Ballistic Missiles (ICBM), Air-Launched Cruise Missile (ALCM), Colombia, and Virginia Class Submarines.

DMEA FY25 SBIR/STTR Accomplishments ($4.143M):
- Secured Advanced Counterfeit Detection & Analysis Capabilities: Advanced component authentication technology to a
Technology Readiness Level of 6, validating its capability in operational environments. By creating an intrinsic, unforgeable
fingerprint from a microchip's unique surface texture, our system provides robust, hardware-level serialization. Established a chain
of custody from the point of origin, significantly enhancing supply chain integrity and providing a powerful countermeasure to
counterfeit components.
- Initiated Automated AI-Powered Manufacturing Processes: Awarded multiple Phase I and Direct to Phase II contracts to develop
a groundbreaking process control and modeling solution for Silicon Carbide (SiC) epitaxy. This initiative leverages in-situ process

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                   FY 2025      FY 2026      FY 2027
monitoring and Artificial Intelligence (AI) to optimize the production of thick epilayers, a foundational material for high-power
devices. The effort is designed to accelerate process development, maximize wafer throughput, and improve material quality for
next-generation systems.
- Launched Development of Ultra-High Voltage Reliability Testing: Commenced a pivotal project to develop a first-of-its-kind
package-level reliability test system for wide-bandgap semiconductor devices. This system will conduct critical high-temperature
and high-humidity stress tests at up to 40kV, addressing a major gap in commercial test capabilities and ensuring the robustness
of components used in extreme operational environments.
- Advanced Next-Generation Pulsed Power System: Advanced solid-state electronics and pulse compression by developing a
next-generation pulsed power system that provides a significant strategic advantage in size, weight, power, and cost (SWaP-
C) over conventional technologies. This innovation delivers unparalleled performance, including higher efficiency, reliability, and
waveform agility, enabling new classes of plasma, particle beam, and laser systems.
- Strengthened Microelectronics Design and Verification: Continued to advance a Phase II SBIR effort developing a methodology
to integrate synthesizable assertions directly into the design and verification flows for FPGAs and integrated circuits, improving
design integrity and reducing verification time for complex microelectronics.

FY 2026 Plans:
DLA FY2026 SBIR/STTR Plans:
-Transition successful Ph I SBIR projects focused on domestic sourcing and/or recycling of Ga and Sc to Ph II.
-Accelerate the development of novel technologies to reduce lead times and production costs for thermal protection systems
crucial to hypersonic platforms.
-Finalize KNO3 pilot production line, achieve LRIP, and deliver product to defense customers. DPA Title III funding will scale the
pilot line from LRIP to full scale production.
-Recover B4C from ~100,000 ESAPI plates to establish the only domestic source of this critical material. Supply B4C to NDS.
Manufacture B4C test articles and subject to small arms ballistics testing at Aberdeen Proving Ground.
-Expand critical mineral work based on strategic alignment within DOD and across USG. Target elements based on projected
need and likelihood of sustainable transition opportunities.
-Focus Weapon System Readiness line of effort on fielded equipment and support of existing weapon systems parts
obsolescence and the current warfighting capabilities aligned with DLA strategic objectives.

DMEA FY26 SBIR/STTR Plans

-Execute Critical Technology Development for High-Power Devices: Continue execution on the Phase II SBIR to develop a
versatile wafer probe system capable of

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                 FY 2025      FY 2026      FY 2027
testing ultra-high-voltage SiC devices up to 40kV. The delivery of the fully functional prototype to DMEA will overcome critical
testing limitations and accelerate the development of next-generation high-power electronics.
- Address Strategic Component Obsolescence: Evaluate proposals and award a Phase II contract for the “3.3/5V Configuration
Logic ASIC” topic to mitigate critical component obsolescence. Concurrently, execute the ongoing Phase II effort for the analysis
and automated re-engineering of obsolete printed circuit board assemblies, ensuring the sustainment of legacy weapon systems.
- Mature AI-Driven Manufacturing and RF Technologies: Transition the AI-powered epitaxy process modeling solution to Phase II,
focusing on implementation and refinement. Continue execution on the "RF Frontend Design (RFE) on Gallium Nitride on Silicon
(GaN-on-Si)" open topic to secure next-generation RF technologies vital for advanced communications and electronic warfare
capabilities.
- Bolster the Domestic Industrial Base: Prepare and release new SBIR/STTR solicitations focused on strategic needs, including
an “Additive Manufacturing Substrate for SatCom Transmitters” and a topic on the “Re-enforcement of PCB Connectors,” to foster
innovation and expand the capabilities of the domestic industrial base.
FY 2027 Plans:
DLA FY2027 SBIR/STTR Plans:
-Transition successful Ph I SBIR projects focused on domestic sourcing and recycling of Ga to Ph II.
-Accelerate the development of novel technologies to reduce lead times and production costs for thermal protection systems
crucial to hypersonic platforms.
-Bring B4C recovery to LRIP status and transition to PEO Soldier for long-term sustainment.
-Expand portfolio into Critical Technology Area Scaled Directed Energy to complement on-going Scaled Hypersonics efforts.
-Expand critical mineral work based on strategic alignment within DOD and across USG. Target elements based on projected
need and likelihood of sustainable transition opportunities.
-Focus Weapon System Readiness line of effort on fielded equipment and support of existing weapon systems parts
obsolescence and the current warfighting capabilities aligned with DLA strategic objectives.

DMEA FY27 SBIR/STTR Plans
- Transition Advanced Manufacturing and Test Capabilities: Drive the transition of successful Phase II technologies—including the
ultra-high voltage reliability test system and the automated wafer probe system—to DMEA programs or to prime contractors for
long-term sustainment and integration into the defense industrial base.
- Expand Application of AI/ML in Microelectronics: Building on the success of the automated epitaxy modeling solution, develop
and release new SBIR/STTR topics focused on applying AI/ML to other critical phases of the microelectronics manufacturing and
testing lifecycle, aiming to further increase production efficiency, quality, and yield.
- Focus on Strategic and Emerging Technology Areas: Develop and release new SBIR/STTR topics based on an analysis of
projected DoW needs and strategic guidance. This will include a continued focus on securing the microelectronics supply chain,

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                             FY 2025      FY 2026      FY 2027
advancing directed energy components, and developing novel materials and manufacturing techniques for hypersonic and space
applications.
- Enhance Weapon System Readiness and Sustainment: Align new topic solicitations with broader DoW strategic objectives to
proactively address parts obsolescence for critical weapon systems, support the sustainment of fielded equipment, and enhance
warfighting capabilities through targeted technological innovation.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
SBIR and STTR tax amounts are based on enacted budgets.
