A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The U.S. Space Command Research and Development program will ensure a comprehensive military advantage in space by integrating existing space capabilities
from the Armed Services and the Intelligence Community with innovations from national laboratories and commercial partners. The program will promote responsible
behavior in space, advocate greater space capabilities, and collaborate with industry partners to achieve national space objectives. This will be accomplished through
the acceleration of technology demonstrations, rapid operational prototyping, and experimentation to increase lethality. The RDT&E program will also conduct
assessments of current and possible future space-based effects via model-based analysis.

The Capability and Verification Environment (CAVE) Lab will support the prioritized analysis of space systems, including:
• Position, Navigation and Timing (PNT)
• Satellite Communications (SATCOM)
• Missile Warning/Golden Dome
• Intelligence, Surveillance, and Reconnaissance (ISR) capabilities and Integration
• Space Domain Awareness (SDA) and sensing needs
• Orbital Warfare systems
• Ground Infrastructure/Command and Control (C2) studies

This will inform service capability roadmaps and funding to meet the required effects for the Space Area of Responsibility (AOR).

This effort is in Budget Activity 4, Advanced Component Development and Prototypes (ACD&P), because efforts are necessary to evaluate integrated technologies,
representative modes or prototype systems in a high fidelity and realistic operating environment.




