    Development & Integration
Remarks
This program is an integral part of the Army Integrated Air and Missile Defense (AIAMD) architecture providing development of a common Integrated Fire Control
Network (IFCN) via modular open systems approach enabling integration of Air Defense Artillery (ADA) components as they become available. This approach enables
the AIAMD program to maintain its baseline program independent of fluctuation of other programs.

D. Acquisition Strategy
Beginning in Fiscal Year 2026, the AIAMD acquisition strategy will diverge into two separate funding paths. A new budget line, PE 0606118A, is being created
specifically for the IBCS Software Acquisition Pathway. Consequently, the existing S40 line will pivot to focus exclusively on supporting the development, integration,
and testing of IBCS Increment 2 and Increment 3 hardware components. This updated strategy merges the legacy AMDPCS and current IBCS capabilities into the new
Increment 3 program. The first project in this program will combine the Engagement Operations Center (EOC) and the tent-based Integrated Collaborative Environment
(ICE) into a single M1087A2 Expando Van. Further projects will adapt these capabilities for other Army vehicles and create an air-droppable version for forward units.
As codified in the approved Increment 3 Capability Development Document (CDD), these hardware modernization efforts are strategically focused on improving the
system's survivability, scalability, and supportability. Survivability will be enhanced by developing components that reduce the system's signature and exposure while
increasing mobility and resiliency. To achieve greater scalability, the strategy employs a Modular Open Systems Approach, allowing for adaptable solutions tailored to
the specific needs of warfighters at different echelons. Finally, supportability investments will focus on mitigating obsolescence, thereby extending the useful life of the
hardware and ensuring the system remains sustainable over the long term.

 The common fires mission command program is the centerpiece of an integrated fires development effort that includes survivability, resiliency, and effectiveness
 improvements against advanced threats from near-peer adversaries. This effort includes IBCS hardware/software integration of IBCS end items. As software is loaded
 onto hardware, testing is conducted to ensure system performance prior to fielding.




